-- в”Ђв”Ђ Cronitor в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cronitor is a developer-focused monitoring platform that tracks cron jobs, website uptime, and heartbeats, alerting teams the instant something fails.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (usage-based per monitor)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small team (fewer than 10 employees)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Berkeley, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cronitor Review 2026: Cron & Uptime Monitoring Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cronitor monitors cron jobs, website uptime, and background processes, and alerts your team the moment something fails; see its 2026 pricing plans.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cronitor is a monitoring platform for developers, founded in March 2014 by Shane Harter and a co-founder after one asked the other how they monitored their own cron jobs at work. The company is headquartered in Berkeley, California, and operates as a small, largely bootstrapped team, in contrast to many venture-funded monitoring competitors. Cronitor's core product captures the status, output, and execution metrics of scheduled jobs (cron jobs, Celery/Sidekiq-style background tasks, and other recurring scripts) and automatically alerts teams when a job fails, runs too long, or вЂ” critically вЂ” never starts at all, a failure mode that traditional logging and exception-tracking tools typically miss. Beyond cron job monitoring, the platform has expanded into general uptime monitoring for websites and APIs, heartbeat/check-in monitoring for any process that can ping an endpoint, and public or private status pages for communicating incidents to customers. The company states it is trusted by more than 50,000 developers and teams, with named customers including Johnson & Johnson, Reddit, Square, and monday.com. Cronitor's pricing follows a freemium, usage-based-per-monitor model. The free 'Hacker' plan includes 5 monitors, email and Slack alerting, a basic status page, and up to 50 status page subscribers, with no time limit. The paid 'Business' plan is pay-as-you-go at $2 per monitor per month plus $5 per user per month, and includes unlimited API requests, up to 10 alert integrations, 12 months of data retention, automated email reports, volume-based discounts as monitor count grows, support for multiple environments, SMS alerts, and premium integrations such as PagerDuty, Opsgenie, and Splunk; optional add-ons include SAML SSO ($5/user/month), branded status pages ($25/month), private status pages ($50/month), and additional status page subscriber capacity. The Business plan includes a 14-day free trial with no commitment required. Enterprise plans start from roughly $6,000 per year on flexible invoice billing and add custom monitoring limits, custom integrations, a dedicated engineer, priority support, and SAML SSO/SCIM access controls included at no extra cost. Cronitor is frequently compared to Healthchecks.io, Dead Man's Snitch, Better Uptime, and Datadog's monitor features, with its main differentiator being a purpose-built focus on scheduled-job and heartbeat monitoring rather than being a broad observability platform, making it a lighter-weight, faster-to-adopt option for engineering teams that primarily need to know when a recurring job silently stops running.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '76ba7a30-adea-4140-9ee6-3e5cd63011ed';

